# AWS EC2 Security Best Practices

## Root Blocking
- **Disable root access:** Only use the root account to create your first IAM user.
- **Enable MFA on the root account.**

## Least Privilege Principle
- Grant only the permissions necessary for users to perform their tasks.

## IAM Roles and Policies
- Use IAM roles for application access to AWS resources.
- Regularly rotate access keys.

## VPC Security
- Configure security groups and network ACLs to control inbound and outbound traffic.
- Deploy instances in a private subnet when possible.

## Instance Security
- Regularly update and patch your instances.
- Implement host-based firewalls.

## Logging and Monitoring
- Enable AWS CloudTrail for auditing and logging API calls.
- Use Amazon CloudWatch for monitoring instance performance and security metrics.

## Data Protection
- Encrypt data at rest and in transit using AWS Key Management Service (KMS).

## Backup and Recovery
- Implement automated backups using Amazon EBS snapshots.

## Incident Response
- Develop an incident response plan and regularly test it.

## Compliance
- Ensure compliance with relevant regulatory requirements (e.g., GDPR, HIPAA).

## Security Benchmarking
- Regularly assess your security posture against AWS security best practices.

## Security Checklist
- [ ] Enable CloudTrail logging.
- [ ] Apply the principle of least privilege.
- [ ] Regularly patch and update instances.
- [ ] Enable multi-factor authentication (MFA).
- [ ] Review IAM roles and permissions regularly.